                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d528">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.115 Radio Corporation of America/8:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="#p_CES1" type="to"
                            >Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-03-03T10:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 3, 1932—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>69. Your 144, March 2, 4 p.m., in regard to radio station at Chenju.</p>
                <p>Department approves your course of action as reported and desires that you follow
                    developments, keeping Department informed. The Radio Corporation has expressed
                    again to Department its interest in the continued operation of this plant.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
